CHILDREN OBESITY IN ENGLAND

measuring and prioritizing the main factors

Introduction

"Today nearly a third of children aged 2 to 15 are overweight or obese, and younger generations are becoming obese at earlier ages and staying obese for longer". By these words the UK government introduced its "Childhood Obesity: a plan for action" report dating back to 2016. Obesity was initally observed as a civilization phenomenon in the 80s in America. Whilst staying limited in Europe, it became a recognised problems in the UK in the 90s and spread across Europe in the new century. Today specialists see it as the number one cause of mortality, having significant impacts on heart desease, cancer and the growing-fast diabetes. The well-known BMI index (the formula is BMI = kg/m2 where kg is a person's weight in kilograms and m2 is their height in metre squared) indicates that 53% of the EU adult population is considered overweight (BMI>25 - Eurostat 2019).

The UK, not showing on this map, is currently at 64% of its adult population being overweight, i.e. in the Top League of "overweight" European countries.

Analyzing the English perspective (*) has 2 benefits from a research standpoint:

    1. It was in the first, if not THE first, European countries to identify the problem and make it a national priority, particularly with respect to childhood obesity. This means heavy research and data available in recent years.
    1. The British government has a very advanced policy on big data and making it widely available to the public, a necessary condition to have access to high-quality data from respected public bodies.

(*): not British, England only for motives of data availability.

OBJECTIVES

The topics of overweight and obesity have been heavily researched to identify cultural, ethnical, spatial (urbanization), economical, social, educational and motivational factors driving this surge in obesity. Recent political focus has been on nutrition (fruit and vegetable) and physical activity. With the quality of the English data, we will try to have a thiner approach to potentially identify more variables in the context of chidren overweight and obesity.

SUMMARY OF FINDINGS

This research investigates 4 aspects of children obesity with 16 different variables: physical activity (6), economical/social (5), nutritional/food related (2) and psycological (3). Our process consisted in comparing the situation of each parameter in the Local Authorities of England. Out of the 308 territories, crossed against each variable, we analyzed approximately 200 values (i.e. local authotities) for each variable. The NHS carries a significant piece of research called "The National Child Measurement Programme (NCMP)": it measures the height and weight of children in reception class (aged 4 to 5) and year 6 (aged 10 to 11), to assess overweight and obesity levels in children within primary schools. The index is BMI, the body mass index. Overweight applies to BMI over 25, whilst obesity starts with a BMI of 30.

Interaction betwwen the 2 children populations

A first regression of 10-11 year old children obesity on 4-5 year old obese showed a very strong correlation between the two. The results are robust and indicate that the percentage of 10-11 year old obese children is 1.8 time the percentage of 4-5 year old children (statistically robust).

One might think it is an expected result. However a similar regression of overweight children between the age of 10-11 years old on 4-5 year old overweight children shows merely no correlation. We have no explanation for these opposite results, only that htey may respond to different stimuli. The purpose of our research is obesity and we focused all the statistical analysis on the 4-5 year old obese children which represent the highest threat to the English nation's health and potentially the root cause to the obesity development.

Social and Psycological = the major interactions

Out of all 16 OLS regressions, 3 psycological factors stand out with an extremely high correlation (and statistically robust _ low CI/P value close to 0):

  • Happiness (measured as "high") with R2 at 0.92
  • Life satisfaction (measured as "low") with R2 at 0.89
  • Anxiety (measured as "high") with R2 at 0.89

This piece of research was conducted by the ONS as part of their Annual Population Survey between January 2017 and December 2019.

On the social side, two variables score at high levels:

  • Motive for unemployment as Long term sickness/disability : R2 at 0.81
  • Motive for unemployment as Looking after family or home : R2 at 0.70
  • Lone Parent Mother: R2 at 0.64

This is part of the census conducted by the ONS and completed in March 2021.

The purely economical criteria performed far less strongly:

  • The Gross Disposable Income per Household (measured in ) has a negative correlation with obesity (beta at -9: each extra of average income in the local authority will reduce the prevalence of obesity by 9 points). However R2 is rather low at 0.17.
  • Job adverts, as an indicator of economic strength in the area, does not show any impact on obesity (beta close to zero, R2 at 0.005).
  • Food bank distribution as another factor to measure poverty: we calculated the number of parcels distributed to children (proportionally to the L.A. population). No conclusion can be made with a high P value on beta. Both beta and correlation very low.

The importance of children physical activity confirmed if need be.

Thanks to on-going research conducted by Sportengland.org (a semi-public organisation), we were able to measure quantity and attitude. On the quantitative front, the correlation is confirmed: R2 of 0.57 for local authorities's with children practising more than 60 minutes a day on average. Similarly a positive correlation appears at 0.47 for children praactising less than 30mn a day. As far as attitude is concerned, two items perform slightly better than the other four: confidence ("I feel confident when I play sports..." - "strongly agree") with an R2 at 0.51 and understanding that "sports is good for me" also with an R2 of 0.51 for children agreeing strongly. Although revealing, the survey conducted leaves with many missing figures for a few local authorities. For that reason, we exclude these variables from linear regression as they reduce substantially the number of observations.

Last but not least, one factor often criticized, the Fast-Food phenomenon. We used a research conducted by Public Health England in 2015 and compared density of Fast Food outlets by 100.000 inhabitants of the local authorities. R2 comes out at 0,19 with a beta at 0.03: it suggests that every increase of the fast food density by 3% increases the children obesity prevalence by 1 point.

Final model: 3 variables

As demonstrated by the stargazer summary, we obtain the best results with only 3 variables as the GDHI (gross disposable household income) variable shows no impact in the multiple regression analysis. All parameters show a 99% confidence interval but the beta for "unemployement for long term sickness or disability". With no zero value in the confidence intervals, we can reject the null on all variables, even if the confidence level on beta "sick" is below 95%.

Subsequently the regression on 3 varaibles gives the following results:

This model enhances the psycological and social factors as main drivers, as well as physical activities of the children. The UK program against obesity is focusing on nutrition (5 portions of fruit and veg per day) and physical activity but does not tackle the social and psycological problems that seem impacting children obesity.

APPENDICES

Data

Major sources of data are the NHS (National Health Service of England), Sportengland (an organization born from this problem to measure and promote physical activity) and Public Health England (governmental). Additional census data was brought in from ONS (Office for National Statistics), UK Data Service and Data.gov.uk (for geographical data). Specific data was added from Trussel Trust (food bank) and Public Health England.

The main information on children obesity is sourced from the NHS: https://digital.nhs.uk/services/national-child-measurement-programme/

ANALYTICAL TOOLS

LOCAL AUHTORITIES

BACKGROUND - SOURCE OF INFORMATION

Local authorities are the finest level of geographical analysis in governmental statistics: kingdom, country, region, county, local authority. There are just over 300 of them in England, which will be the base of our search for variances and possible relationship with multiple factors.

This analysis is on the geographic level, not time based, comparing situations between local authorities on various inputs and outputs. A file with all local authorities' codes and names is produced from a more extensive 'gov UK file'. Downloaded from: www.data.gov.uk/dataset/379b60d5-711a-4c54-8900-fb5151240a0a/ward-to-local-authority-district-to-county-to-region-to-country-december-2022-lookup-in-united-kingdom

CHILDREN OBESITY

BMI

BACKGROUND - SOURCE OF INFORMATION

The NHS report presents findings from the Government's National Child Measurement Programme (NCMP) for England, 2022/23 school year. It covers children in Reception aged 4-5 years, codified R, and Year 6, aged 10-11 years (codified 6) in mainstream schools in England. The report contains analyses of Body Mass Index (BMI) classification rates by age, sex, deprivation and ethnicity as well as geographic analyses. Although there are differences by gender and by ethnicity, we have excluded these from the research has they were not reported in other sources, focus of this analysis.Full report available in Excel tables at https://digital.nhs.uk/data-and-information/publications/statistical/national-child-measurement-programme/2022-23-school-year

R: Children aged 4 to 5 years old

# Loading "Enjoy" data and cleaning
csvfile = pd.read_csv('ActiveLivesDataExport_Enjoyment - Enjoy taking part in exercise and sports (years 3-11) - Strongly agree.csv', skiprows=3)
sportenjoy = pd.DataFrame(csvfile)
sportenjoy.rename(columns = {sportenjoy.columns[0]: 'LA name',"Academic Year 21-22":"strongly_agree"}, inplace = True)
sportenjoy.drop(columns = ["Academic Year 17-18","Academic Year 18-19","Academic Year 19-20","Academic Year 20-21"], inplace = True)

# Selecting the right L.A.
sportenjoy = sportenjoy[sportenjoy['LA name'].str.endswith(' LA')]
sportenjoy['LA name'] = sportenjoy['LA name'].str[:-3]
sportenjoy = sportenjoy[sportenjoy['LA name'].isin(la_select['LAD22NM'])]
sportenjoy = pd.merge(sportenjoy, la_select_short, on = 'LA name')

In[]:

ECONOMICAL / SOCIAL PARAMETERS OF THE HOUSEHOLD

BACKGROUND - SOURCE OF INFORMATION

Most of the information is originating from the Office for National Statistics (https://www.ons.gov.uk), using their search engine at https://www.ons.gov.uk/search?q=local+authority. Dates vary from 2019 to 2022 with one exception which is Gross Disposable Household Income per head by Local Authority, with the last edition dating from 2016. Most data comes out in Excel tables.

The Gross Disposable Household Income per head by Local Authority has not been retrieved since 2016. However, this is an important measure of household wealth, so we maintained it in our analysis assuming little changes in a matter of few years at the Local Authority level.
In[36]:
# Loading GDHI file
xlfile = pd.read_excel('Gross Disposable Household Income per head by LA.xlsx')
gdhi = pd.DataFrame(xlfile)
gdhi.drop(columns = ["Region"], inplace = True)

# Selecting the right L.A. and checking quality
gdhi.rename(columns = {'LAU1 code': 'LA code', 2016: 'GDHI'}, inplace = True)
gdhi = gdhi[gdhi['LA code'].isin(la_select['LAD22CD'])]

# Regression of obesity
gdhi_reg = gdhi[gdhi['LA code'].isin(la_select['LAD22CD'])]
reg_data = 'Q("Obes4-5y") ~ Q("GDHI")'
reg3 = smf.ols(formula = reg_data, data = pd.merge(obesity, gdhi_reg, how = 'inner', left_on = 'LA code', right_on = 'LA code'))
result = reg3.fit()
result.summary()

xlfile = pd.read_excel('Job adverts by LA -Jan 22.xlsx')

# Merging with weight info for regression purposes
data = pd.merge(obesity, job_adverts, how = 'inner', on = 'LA code')
reg_data = 'Q("Obes4-5y") ~ Q("job_adverts")'
reg6 = smf.ols(formula = reg_data, data = data)
result = reg6.fit()
result.summary()

In[]:

FOOD ENVIRONMENT

Limited information publicly available at Local Authority level:

  • Food bank distribution from the Trussel Trust
  • Fast food presence in numbr of outlets

FOOD BANK DISTRIBUTION FROM THE TRUSSEL TRUST

Data selected: April 2021 to March 2022. We did not use 20-21 affected by the covid pandemic, nor the most recent April 22 to March 23, too distant form other datasets.

NOTES ON THE TRUSSEL TRUST

Trussel Trust are the very dominant food bank in the UK with over 400 distribution centers. From the Trussel Trust file: "These tables include information on the number of emergency food parcels that were distributed to people across the United Kingdom between the 1 April and 31 March for 2017/18, 2019/20, 2020/21, 2021/22, and 2022/23. These statistics are a measure of volume rather than unique users. The data is collected using an online system into which food banks enter data from each food bank voucher, and the number of emergency food parcels is recorded. Data is presented as a cumulative total of all parcels distributed throughout the year. Parcels refer to the number of emergency food parcels distributed by food banks. These can either provide three-days or seven-days worth of supplies. No equivalisation has taken place to scale seven-day parcels down to three. Food parcels are linked to the local authority based on where the distribution centre is based, rather than where the person needing support is living. I.e. if a person living in Bromley receives a parcel from a food bank in Lambeth the parcel is recorded in these statistics under Lambeth."

# Loading file on food banks
xlfile = pd.read_excel('Food Distribution by LA.xlsx')
food_bank = pd.DataFrame(xlfile)
food_bank.rename(columns = {'Local Authority':'LA name'}, inplace = True)
food_bank.drop(columns = ["Region", "Number of parcels for adults", "Number of distribution centres"], inplace = True)
food_bank = food_bank[food_bank['LA name'].isin(la_select['LAD22NM'])]
food_bank = food_bank[pd.to_numeric(food_bank['Number of parcels for children'], errors = 'coerce').notna()]

# Merging with "population" file for ratio purposes
food_bank = pd.merge(food_bank, population, on = "LA name")
food_bank["parcels/1000 inhab."] = (food_bank["Number of parcels for children"] / food_bank["Pop 2021"] * 1000).round(2)

# Loading "anxiety" file
xlfile = pd.read_excel('Anxiety by LA.xlsx')
anxiety = pd.DataFrame(xlfile)
anxiety = anxiety.dropna(subset = ['Geography code'])

# Selecting the right L.A.
anxiety = anxiety[anxiety['Geography code'].str.startswith('E')]
anxiety = anxiety[anxiety['Geography code'].isin(la_select['LAD22CD'])]
anxiety = anxiety[['Geography code', 'High']]
anxiety.rename(columns = {'Geography code':'LA code','High':'High_anxiety'}, inplace = True)

In[63]:
# Checking quality
data['low_happiness'] = pd.to_numeric(data['low_happiness'], errors = 'coerce')
data['sick'] = pd.to_numeric(data['sick'], errors = 'coerce')
data['family'] = pd.to_numeric(data['family'], errors = 'coerce')
data['lone_mother'] = pd.to_numeric(data['lone_mother'], errors = 'coerce')
In[66]:
# Regressions on 4 variables
rega = smf.ols(formula="obesity ~ low_happiness", data=data).fit()
regb = smf.ols(formula="obesity ~ sick", data=data).fit()
regc = smf.ols(formula="obesity ~ family", data=data).fit()
regd = smf.ols(formula="obesity ~ GDIH", data=data).fit()

stargazer = Stargazer([rega, regb, regc, regd])
stargazer.covariate_order(["low_happiness", "sick", "family", "GDIH", "Intercept"])
stargazer.rename_covariates({"Intercept": "Constant"})
stargazer
